Logging is in and verified. Each request now produces one line with method, path+query, request body (for POSTs), status, latency, client IP, and the response body:

```
POST /api/v1/sensor/readings req={"latitude":40.7128,...} -> 201 in 1ms from ::1 resp={"latitude":40.7128,...,"timestamp":1784509642}
GET /api/v1/weather?lat=40.71&lon=-74.01 -> 200 in 578ms from ::1 resp={"current_temperature":72,...}
GET /api/v1/weather?lat=40.71&lon=-74.01 -> 401 in 0s from ::1 resp={"error":"unauthorized"}
```

How it works: a `requestLogger` middleware in `cmd/server/main.go` reads and restores the request body, wraps Gin's response writer to capture what handlers write, and emits one `log.Print` line after the handler runs. It replaces Gin's default logger (`gin.New()` + `gin.Recovery()` instead of `gin.Default()`), so there are no duplicate access-log lines.

On hiding the API key: the middleware never logs headers at all — that's the only place the key appears (it's not in the URL or bodies), so it can't leak. I verified this directly by grepping the log for the test key after sending authorized, unauthorized, and invalid requests: zero hits.

Two details: JSON bodies are compacted onto one line, and bodies are truncated at 2 KB (with a `...(N bytes total)` marker) so a large history response can't flood the log. `docker logs tidbit-backend` will show these once deployed.

